('ffcdbe2b-d959-480b-b78f-ffc1634f7b01', 'What is the JavaScript Event Loop?', 'ffcdbe2b-d959-480b-b78f-ffc1634f7b01-Oi8yRq', NULL, 'JavaScript is a single-threaded language.
After receiving the script file JS’s engine starts to execute. When JS goes through the execution phase, Whenever it found a synchronous function and took it to the call stack. If any asynchronous function(setTimeout/fetch/Promise/async-await) or event listeners have inside it, then JS simply handover these async functions to browsers'' web API. After that call stack executes normally in a synchronous way. So basically the web API transfers these call-back functions to the call-back queue after the end of the timer. And also transfer to micro-tasks like Promise, and async-await to the microtask queue.
After executing all of the synchronous functions in the call stack then here comes the Event Loop. Event loop first through loops on microtask queue, take the functions or anything to the call stack to run like Promise/async-await. After that, the event loop takes call-back functions from the call-back queue to the call stack and executes.
The Microtask queue has a higher priority than the call-back queue.', NULL, 'f', NULL, NULL, '6ffc4a0c-662c-402b-8b5c-420f8de81a87', '2022-07-19 09:35:24', '2022-07-19 09:36:05', '2022-07-19 09:35:24');

